<BlogPost
	title="Boston to Old Orchard Beach by Car: The Complete Guide"
	description="About 95 miles up I-95. What to know about traffic, tolls, road trip stops, and why Saco makes a better base than staying right in Old Orchard Beach."
	date="April 2026"
	category="Travel Guide"
	slug="boston-to-old-orchard-beach"
	heroImage={heroImg}
>
	<p>Old Orchard Beach is about 96 miles from Boston on I-95. Under two hours in good traffic. On a summer Friday afternoon, plan for three to four. The guests who've done this drive the most know when to leave and when not to. This is what they know.</p>

	<h2>The Route</h2>

	<p>Straightforward: Boston to I-93 North to I-95 North through New Hampshire to the Maine Turnpike (also I-95) to Exit 35, Saco. From Exit 35, you're about five minutes from Saco Bay Hotel and ten minutes from the Old Orchard Beach pier. The Maine Turnpike begins at the New Hampshire border in Kittery.</p>

	<h2>Actual Drive Times</h2>

	<p>In normal conditions: 1 hour 37 to 48 minutes. Summer Friday afternoon: 2.5 to 4 hours. I-95 northbound through New Hampshire and into Maine is consistently heavy from roughly 2 PM through 8 PM. From Portland, Maine: 20 minutes.</p>

	<p>Leaving Boston before 10 AM or after 7:30 PM on a summer Friday changes the experience completely. Midday Saturday and Sunday are manageable in both directions. The people who've figured this out are the ones who show up at the hotel looking relaxed on a Friday evening.</p>

	<h2>Tolls</h2>

	<p>Both New Hampshire and Maine charge tolls on I-95. Maine takes cash and E-ZPass at all plazas. No all-electronic pay-by-plate, so you won't get a bill in the mail if you forget your transponder.</p>

	<p>Maine Turnpike full length (Kittery to Augusta): $7.00 cash, roughly $6.05 to $6.70 with E-ZPass. New Hampshire Turnpike (I-95 through NH): about $4.00 total northbound. Total tolls Boston to Saco one way: roughly $6 to $10 depending on how you pay. A Maine-issued E-ZPass offers up to 40 percent off for frequent travelers (40-plus trips per month), worth it if you come up multiple times a season.</p>

	<h2>Stops Worth Making</h2>

	<h3>Portsmouth, NH (about 56 miles from Boston)</h3>

	<p>Exit 7 from I-95, roughly 40 minutes outside Boston. Cobblestone streets, local restaurants, craft breweries, the Strawbery Banke Museum. A good breakfast or lunch stop before the Maine border. Portsmouth is a legitimately good small city that most people drive past without stopping.</p>

	<h3>Kittery Outlets (about 65 miles from Boston)</h3>

	<p>Right at the Maine border, Exit 3 or Exit 2. Over 120 name-brand outlet stores: Nike, Coach, lululemon, Eddie Bauer, Crate and Barrel, Kittery Trading Post. Savings of 25 to 65 percent. Budget an hour if anyone in the car needs new sandals before the beach.</p>

	<h3>Kennebunk and Kennebunkport (about 81 miles from Boston)</h3>

	<figure>
		<Image src={lobsterImg} alt="Maine lobster roll, a good stop in Kennebunkport or at the OOB pier" loading="lazy" width={1200} height={700} />
		<figcaption>A lobster roll stop in Kennebunkport or at the OOB pier is a good reason to leave Boston early and take your time.</figcaption>
	</figure>

	<p>Exit 25. Upscale coastal village with good restaurants in Dock Square. Goose Rocks Beach and Kennebunk Beach are nearby if you want a preview of the Maine coast before you arrive. Good for a lunch stop before the last stretch into Saco.</p>

	<h2>Parking at Old Orchard Beach</h2>

	<figure>
		<Image src={oobBeachImg} alt="Old Orchard Beach on a busy summer day with the pier visible" loading="lazy" width={1600} height={900} />
		<figcaption>OOB on a peak summer day. Parking is the main challenge for anyone driving in without a hotel nearby.</figcaption>
	</figure>

	<p>This is the part of the trip that catches people off guard the first time.</p>

	<p>Municipal lots and street parking run $3 per hour, Memorial Day through Labor Day. Private lots near the pier charge $20 to $40 on peak summer weekends. Cheaper lots further from the pier run $5 to $10. Free residential street parking exists on the side streets north and south of downtown, about a 10 to 15 minute walk. Milliken Street area is the local tip: steps from the beach, usually less crowded than the main lots.</p>

	<p>Get there before 9 AM on summer weekends to secure parking before the lots fill. On July 4th weekend, this is not negotiable. Convenient parking is gone by early afternoon.</p>

	<h2>The Amtrak Downeaster</h2>

	<p>If you'd rather not drive, the Amtrak Downeaster runs from Boston North Station to Old Orchard Beach station, which sits within 100 yards of the beach. Travel time: about 2 hours 11 minutes. Fares starting at $28 to $32 one way. Station address: 11 First Street, Old Orchard Beach, ME 04064. Seasonal service approximately May through mid-October. Not all trains stop at OOB. Check the timetable at amtrakdowneaster.com. Sample schedule: Train 681 departs Boston 8:50 AM, arrives OOB 11:25 AM.</p>

	<p>For a day trip from Boston, the train eliminates parking costs and Friday traffic entirely. It's the better option if your schedule allows it.</p>

	<h2>Why Saco Works Better Than Staying in OOB</h2>

	<figure>
		<Image src={pierImg} alt="Old Orchard Beach pier, 10 minutes from Saco Bay Hotel" loading="lazy" width={1200} height={700} />
		<figcaption>The OOB pier is 10 minutes from the hotel. Close enough for a morning beach day, far enough to step back from resort-town pricing and noise at night.</figcaption>
	</figure>

	<p>Old Orchard Beach in July is a resort town operating at full capacity. Great for a day out. Intense for multiple nights. Saco sits directly next to OOB, and Maine Turnpike Exit 35 drops you straight into Saco. It's the natural first stop off the highway.</p>

	<p>From Saco Bay Hotel, the OOB pier is a 10-minute drive. Funtown Splashtown is 1.5 miles away. Ferry Beach State Park is 2 miles. Downtown Biddeford, with some of the most acclaimed restaurants in Maine, is 10 minutes. You can spend your days at the beach and evenings somewhere completely different. Most guests who've done it both ways prefer the Saco setup.</p>

	<div class="tip-box">
		<strong>Before You Leave Boston</strong>
		<p>Check the Maine Turnpike's real-time travel time data at maineturnpike.com. The gap between leaving at 11 AM versus 3 PM on a summer Friday is often 45 to 90 minutes. If you can get out before noon, you'll arrive before the heavy traffic builds and before the parking lots fill.</p>
	</div>
</BlogPost>
